This is the heartstopping moment a climber made a wrong move which sent him plunging down an icy <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cliff" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cliff" target="_blank">cliff</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Face" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Face" target="_blank">face</a> as he scaled a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Scottish_Gaelic" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Scottish_Gaelic" target="_blank">Scottish</a> mountainKarlis Bardelis 30 from Latvia was attempting to climb a 60 metre <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cliff" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cliff" target="_blank">cliff</a> in Coire an Lochain <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Scotland_Yard" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Scotland_Yard" target="_blank">Scotland</a> during a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Training" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Training" target="_blank">training</a> exerciseFootage from a camera attached to Karlis's <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Helmet" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Helmet" target="_blank">helmet</a> shows his <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ice_axe" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ice_axe" target="_blank">ice axe</a> coming loose  knocking his other <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Axe" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Axe" target="_blank">axe</a> out of positionThe keen climber then begins a terrifying threeandahalf second tenmetre free fall before his safety ropes catch him Footage from the training exercise in 2012 has only been released but highlights the potential <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Risk" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Risk" target="_blank">dangers</a> involved in the popular sportKarlis who now works in <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nepal" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nepal" target="_blank">Nepal</a> said &quotMy ropes saved me and stopped my <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autumn" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Autumn" target="_blank">fall</a>&quotThese kind of falls are very dangerous because I'm carrying two <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ice" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ice" target="_blank">ice</a> tools and <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crampons" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crampons" target="_blank">crampons</a> both of which are really sharp and could cause serious <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Injury" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Injury" target="_blank">injuries</a>&quotObviously there's the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Risk" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Risk" target="_blank">risk</a> of hitting a rock on my way down which can cause serious fractures&quotI never think that I'm going to die in these situations which is why I never consider <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Death_%28personification%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Death_%28personification%29" target="_blank">death</a> as an option&quot Karlis had travelled to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Scotland_Yard" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Scotland_Yard" target="_blank">Scotland</a> to take part in a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Training" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Training" target="_blank">training</a> course organised by the British Mountaineering Council joining <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Climbing" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Climbing" target="_blank">climbers</a> from 26 countriesAnd he attempted the level six climb with some trepidationHe said &quotI was <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Feeling" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Feeling" target="_blank">feeling</a> excited about that climb but at the same <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Time" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Time" target="_blank">time</a> I was <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Feeling" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Feeling" target="_blank">feeling</a> scared in those difficult parts too&quotI fell because I made a mistake I put one <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ice_axe" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ice_axe" target="_blank">ice axe</a> in a crack and was trying to put another one in but the placement wasn't <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Good_%28economics%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Good_%28economics%29" target="_blank">good</a> so it ripped the other one out&quotMy <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crampons" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crampons" target="_blank">crampons</a> weren't in a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Stable" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Stable" target="_blank">stable</a> place so I fell&quot The footage shows Karlis tumble backwards from the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cliff" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cliff" target="_blank">cliff</a> <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Face" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Face" target="_blank">face</a> and free fall towards the groundHe said &quotI was just thinking 'I hope I <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Landscape" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Landscape" target="_blank">land</a> somewhere soft and don't break any bones'&quotIncredibly after being saved by his harness Karlis continued his ascent after the fallHe said &quotI climbed back to the same place and this time did it right using the same technique&quotSome <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/People_%28magazine%29" target="_blank">people</a> laugh when they see the video  others say they are not going to <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sleep" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sleep" target="_blank">sleep</a> after seeing it&quotI guess it was a <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Good_%28economics%29" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Good_%28economics%29" target="_blank">good</a> example of how not to climb&quot
</div>
